SIMPLE: swim
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swim
<hw>Swim</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Swam</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Swum</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>;
<pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Swum</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Swimming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>swimman</ets>; akin to
D. <ets>zwemmen</ets>, OHG. <ets>swimman</ets>, G. <ets>schwimmen</ets>,
Icel. <ets>svimma</ets>, Dan. <ets>sw⟦oum⟧mme</ets>, Sw.
<ets>simma</ets>. Cf. <er>Sound</er> an air bladder, a strait.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To be supported by water or other fluid; not to sink;
to float; <as>as, any substance will <ex>swim</ex>, whose specific
gravity is less than that of the fluid in which it is
immersed</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move progressively in water by means of strokes
with the hands and feet, or the fins or the tail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Leap in with me into this angry flood,⟦br⟧
And <qex>swim</qex> to yonder point.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be overflowed or drenched.</def> <rj><au>Ps. vi.
6.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sudden the ditches swell, the meadows <qex>swim</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Fig.: To be as if borne or floating in a
fluid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] now <qex>swim</qex> in joy.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To be filled with swimming animals.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Streams] that <qex>swim</qex> full of small fishes.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swim
<hw>Swim</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pass or move over or
on by swimming; <as>as, to <ex>swim</ex> a stream</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sometimes he thought to <qex>swim</qex> the stormy main.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause or compel to swim; to make to float;
<as>as, to <ex>swim</ex> a horse across a river</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To immerse in water that the lighter parts may
float; <as>as, to <ex>swim</ex> wheat in order to select
seed</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Swim
<hw>Swim</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of swimming; a
gliding motion, like that of one swimming.</def> <rj><au>B.
Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The sound, or air bladder, of a fish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A part of a stream much frequented by fish.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Swim bladder</b></col>, <cd>an air bladder of a
fish.</cd> -- <col><b>To be in the swim</b></col>, <cd>to be in a
favored position; to be associated with others in active affairs.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Swim
<hw>Swim</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>swime</ets> dizziness,
vertigo, AS. <ets>sw⟦imac⟧ma</ets>; akin to D. <ets>zwijm</ets>, Icel.
<ets>svimi</ets> dizziness, <ets>svina</ets> to subside,
<ets>sv⟦imac⟧a</ets> to abate, G. <ets>schwindel</ets> dizziness,
<ets>schwinden</ets> to disappear, to dwindle, OHG.
<ets>sw⟦imac⟧nan</ets> to dwindle. Cf. <er>Squemish</er>,
<er>Swindler</er>.]</ety> <def>To be dizzy; to have an unsteady or
reeling sensation; <as>as, the head <ex>swims</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swimbel</ent>⟦br⟧
